body:
### Describe the bug

I can set trigger (cloud event filter that triggers Funqy Knative Events function) via `io.quarkus.funqy.knative.events.CloudEventMapping#trigger`, if I don't do that, function name is used as trigger. I defined additional attribute filter with `@EventAttribute`, used function name as `trigger` and received an exception. The documentation doesn't mention `@EventAttribute` single time (see https://github.com/quarkusio/quarkus/issues/28490), so I don't know what expected behavior is. https://github.com/quarkusio/quarkus/pull/17655 that added the attribute provides context on what author intention was, but doesn't explain why I can't use function name.

### Expected behavior

Exception is not thrown, filter is applied. Or documentation correct my expectations (please kindly explain reasons for such behavior).


### Actual behavior

An exception is thrown
```bash
...
Caused by: java.lang.IllegalStateException: Function for trigger 'bar' has multiple matching invokers
...
```

### How to Reproduce?

Reproducer:

Steps to reproduce the behavior:
1. use `funqy-knative-events-quickstart`
2. add functions below to `org.acme.funqy.SimpleFunctionChain`
```Java
    @Funq
    @CloudEventMapping(attributes = {
            @EventAttribute(name = "custom", value = "bar") })
    public String bar(String input) {
        return "bar";
    }

    @Funq
    @CloudEventMapping(trigger = "bar", attributes = {
            @EventAttribute(name = "custom", value = "foo") })
    public String foo(String input) {
        return "foo";
    }
```

On the other hand, if you set `trigger = "bar"` to `org.acme.funqy.SimpleFunctionChain#bar`, everything works as (I) expected.

